rca of the issue:
MobileHandoffModal.jsx polling useEffect declares `let cancelled = false;` and its cleanup sets `cancelled = true`. When the poll detects used=true, it calls setState('consumed') then schedules setTimeout(onClose, 2200). React re-runs the effect due to state change; the previous effect's cleanup fires and sets cancelled=true; the setTimeout closure captures this outer `cancelled`, so `if (!cancelled) onClose?.()` never runs. FIX: split into two effects — keep polling in one (deps: [state, magicToken]) and put the auto-close timer in a separate effect keyed on `state === 'consumed'` with its own timer id cleanup, e.g.:

useEffect(() => {
  if (state !== 'consumed') return;
  const id = setTimeout(() => onClose?.(), 2200);
  return () => clearTimeout(id);
}, [state, onClose]);

Reproduction: (1) login as admin, (2) click 'Continue on Mobile', (3) POST /api/auth/consume-magic with the modal's token from another client; observe modal transitions to consumed state + shows Android label + toast, but stays visible >6s.
